For n = p^k, any multiplicative partition uses factors p^{a_i} with a_i ≥ 1 and ∑ a_i = k. This gives a partition of k, and conversely, any partition of k yields a multiplicative partition of p^k. Hence P(p^k) = p(k), the ordinary partition number of k.

Since 64 = 2^6, P(64) = p(6) = 11.

\boxed{11}
